This notebook preprocesses data from the Vital Statistics Natality Birth Data. It first takes a working subset of the raw source CSV and parses the columns to their correct types (binary, numeric, ordered or unordered factor).

A new variable smoking is created with three levels, none, light, heavy. Three datasets are created.

  1. Binary treatment smoking_light, this dataset only contains light and non-smokers.
  2. Binary treatment smoking_heavy, this dataset only contains heavy and non-smokers.
  3. Continuous treatment cigar (number of cigarettes smoked per day).

We filter all of these to a subset where our treatment and outcome variable dbirwt (birth weight) are non-missing since they cannot be for the purposes of our analysis, and then sample 100,000 records for analysis.

Finally, we select our covariates of interest to control for confounding and encode those that are unordered factors. For factors with <10 levels, we use a one-hot encoding. For factors with 10+ levels (three state-level geographic identifiers and the fathers and mothers race), a 6 dimensional sparse encoding obtained using SPCA on the continuous covariates is used. This encoding is one of the forms of sufficient representation discussed in (TODO CITE sufrep).

Subset and preprocess data

# In theory variable, currently only 2002 preprocessing implemented
year <- 2002

# Data size for analysis: 100,000
data_size <- as.integer(1e5)

To begin with we sample a subset of birth records uniformly at random. We sample more than the desired data_size so that there is enough data remaining after preprocessing and filtering. Sampling at this stage speeds up the following steps since the full dataset is quite large (1.8GB).

subset <- FALSE

subset_fname <- paste0("data/subset_rds/natl", year, ".rds")

if (subset) {
  raw_fname <- paste0("data/raw_csv/natl", year, ".csv")
  set.seed(50)
  # select a random sample
  natl_raw <- 
    read_csv(raw_fname, col_types = cols(.default = col_character())) %>%
    sample_n(2 * data_size) # larger sample so dropping some data leaves enough

  write_rds(natl_raw, subset_fname, compress = "gz")
}

Convert text csv to factors using preprocessing code from preprocess_natl2002.R. This mostly just fixes the factor levels to match those described in the data documentation. It does make some changes to two variables as noted at the top of the preprocessing code.

Also filter to singleton births and add treatment variables.

preprocess <- TRUE

preprocessed_fname <- paste0("data/preprocessed_rds/natl", year, ".rds")

if (preprocess) {
  source(paste0("preprocess/preprocess_natl", year, ".R"))
  natl_full <- read_rds(subset_fname) %>%
    
    # preprocess natl, fix types / levels and modify variables (monpre, dmar)
    preprocess_natl() %>%
    
    # filter to singleton births to maintain independent samples
    filter(dplural == 1) %>%
    
    # add NEW variables
    mutate(
      smoking = case_when(
        cigar ==  0 ~ "none",
        cigar <  10 ~ "light",
        cigar >= 10 ~ "heavy") %>%
        factor(levels = c("none", "light", "heavy")),
      smoking_heavy = smoking == "heavy",
      smoking_light = smoking == "light")
    
  write_rds(natl_full, preprocessed_fname, compress = "gz")
}

natl_full <- read_rds(preprocessed_fname)

Prepare Data

Here we select our covariates to control for confounding. Since the original natality dataset contains multiple codings for the same features, here we select a single coding per variable of interest.

Datasets are created with the following treatments.

  1. Binary treatment smoking_light, this dataset only contains light and non-smokers.
  2. Binary treatment smoking_heavy, this dataset only contains heavy and non-smokers.
  3. Continuous treatment cigar (number of cigarettes smoked per day).
# Covariate names
Xnames <- unlist(covariates)
names(Xnames) <- NULL # otherwise select renames columns below

# Prepare datasets
set.seed(50)
natl <- list()

# treatment types (we replicate the encoding for each one)
treatments <- c("smoking_light", "smoking_heavy", "cigar")

natl[["smoking_light"]] <- natl_full %>%
  filter(!smoking_heavy) %>% # remove heavy smokers
  select(all_of(c(Xnames, "dbirwt", "smoking_light"))) %>% # select variables
  drop_na(all_of(c("dbirwt", "smoking_light"))) %>% # Y, W are not NA
  sample_n(data_size) # select num. of samples for analysis

natl[["smoking_heavy"]] <- natl_full %>%
  filter(!smoking_light) %>% # remove light smokers
  select(all_of(c(Xnames, "dbirwt", "smoking_heavy"))) %>% # select variables
  drop_na(all_of(c("dbirwt", "smoking_heavy"))) %>% # Y, W are not NA
  sample_n(data_size) # select num. of samples for analysis

natl[["cigar"]] <- natl_full %>%
  select(all_of(c(Xnames, "dbirwt", "cigar"))) %>% # select variables
  drop_na(all_of(c("dbirwt", "cigar"))) %>% # Y, W are not NA
  sample_n(data_size) # select num. of samples for analysis

# save model data
for (treat in treatments) {
  natl_fname <- paste0("models/natl/natl", year, ".", treat, ".rds")
  write_rds(natl$smoking_light, natl_fname, compress = "gz")
}

The top 7 missing variables are mothers place of birth, population size of county of occurrence, fathers race, origin, and age, and the mothers vaginal herpes and uterine bleeding status. All other variables are missing in less than 6% of samples. (The continuous treatment data is shown in this example, but the two binary treatment datasets are similar.)

natl$cigar %>%
  summarise(across(.fns = function (x) sum(is.na(x)) / length(x))) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = everything()) %>%
  arrange(desc(value)) %>%
  rename(fracNA = value) %>%
  head(10)

Note that missing values in this dataset can be due to a variety of factors. A large proportion of missingness is explained by regional variations in reporting, and this and other factors lead many variable pairs to have a high missingness correlation.

set.seed(245)
M <- natl$cigar %>%
  sample_n(1000) %>%
  summarise(across(.fns = is.na)) %>%
  remove_constant() %>%
  cor()

# plot NA fraction correlations
corrplot(M, method="circle", order="hclust", tl.col = "black", tl.cex = 0.5)

Factor Representation / Group Encoding

Our models will require exclusively numeric-valued inputs, and we therefore need to encode group-valued variables as numeric. First we split the data into variables that can be directly converted to numbers (i.e.numeric values, ordered factors, and binary factors) from those that require group encoding.

natl_num <- list() # numeric variables
natl_grp <- list() # group variables

for (treat in treatments) {
  # numeric and binary values
  natl_num_bin <- natl[[treat]] %>% 
    select_if(function (col) (is.numeric(col) || is.logical(col))) %>%
    transmute(across(everything(), ~ as.numeric(.)))
  
  # ordered factors
  natl_ord <- natl[[treat]] %>% 
    select_if(function (col) (is.factor(col) && is.ordered(col))) %>%
    # preserve numeric coding of factor levels instead of level index
    transmute(across(everything(), ~ as.numeric(as.character(.))))
  
  # combine ordered types
  natl_num[[treat]] <- bind_cols(natl_num_bin, natl_ord)
  
  # unordered factors that need encoding
  natl_grp[[treat]] <- natl[[treat]] %>%
    select(-one_of(names(natl_num[[treat]]))) # drop numeric cols
}

Note that simply using one-hot encoding would massively expands the number of variables since some of our group variables have many levels (i.e.50+ states).

natl_grp_nlevels <- list()

for (treat in treatments) {
  natl_grp_nlevels[[treat]] <- sapply(natl_grp[[treat]], nlevels)
}

natl_grp_nlevels$cigar
restatus stnatexp stresexp   ormoth    mrace   mplbir   orfath    frace 
       4       57       61        6       16       56        6       16 
    csex 
       2

Most of the one-hot dimensions come from stnatexp, stresexp, and mplbir, all of which are geographic variables. The race variables mrace and frace also contribute many group levels / dimensions. For these variables specifically, it would be helpful to use alternate encodings.

One alternate class of encoding schemes, sufficient representations, are described in (TODO CITE sufrep). We define different encoding types for the group variables based on their level counts. For factors with <10 levels, we use a one-hot encoding. For factors with 10+ levels (three state-level geographic identifiers and the fathers and mothers race), a 6 dimensional sparse encoding obtained using SPCA on groupwise means of the continuous covariates is used.

natl_grp_encoding_types <- list()

for (treat in treatments) {
  natl_grp_encoding_types[[treat]] <- natl_grp_nlevels[[treat]] %>%
    map(function(nlevels) {
      # use sparse low rank where one-hot would be "too" high dimensional
      if (nlevels < 10) "one_hot" else "sparse_low_rank"
    })
}

We then generate encoders of these types. Note that our modification of the sufrep code currently encodes the NAs in the factor G as a separate level. An alternate approach would be to leave NA values NA in all their dimensions. It also drops NA values in X in the means encoding to which SPCA is applied.

# Make sure we have our modified make_encoder that works with NA covariates in X
source("make_encoder.R")
natl_grp_encoders <- list()

for (treat in treatments) {
  natl_grp_encoders[[treat]] <- 
    map2(natl_grp_encoding_types[[treat]], natl_grp[[treat]],
         function(encoding, G) {
           make_encoder(encoding,
                        X = as.matrix(select(natl_num[[treat]],
                                             -all_of(c("dbirwt", treat)))), 
                        G = G, num_components = 6)
         })
}

Generate the corresponding encodings on our data.

natl_grp_encodings <- list()

for (treat in treatments) {
  natl_grp_encodings[[treat]] <- natl_grp_encoders[[treat]] %>%
    map2(natl_grp[[treat]], # apply encoder function .x
         ~ as.data.frame(
           .x(X = as.matrix(select(natl_num[[treat]], -all_of(c("dbirwt", treat)))),
              G = .y))) %>%
    map2_dfc(names(natl_grp[[treat]]), # rename columns "varname.dim"
             ~ rename_with(.x, function (x) paste(.y, 1:length(.x), sep=".")))
}

Finally, recombine with the numeric variables to give our data matrix.

natl_rep <- list()

for (treat in treatments) {
  # combine numeric and encoded group variables
  natl_rep[[treat]] <- bind_cols(natl_num[[treat]], natl_grp_encodings[[treat]])
  
  # save model data
  natl_rep_fname <- paste0("models/natl_rep/natl", year, ".", treat, ".rds")
  write_rds(natl_rep[[treat]], natl_rep_fname, compress = "gz")
}
